Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Access, Guaranty Trust, Zenith Bank

-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 
2011-03-22T13:24:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-22/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-access-guaranty-trust-zenith-bank.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index rallied the most in more than two months, adding 1.7
percent to 24,973.14 by 2:23 p.m. in Lagos, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  Kenya ’s All-Share Index retreated for a fourth day, losing
0.3 percent to 72.46 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. Mauritius’s
SEMDEX Index rallied 1.3 percent to 1,971.17 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
retreated 0.5 percent to 1,059.53 by 1:23 p.m. in Accra, a
second day of decreases. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
gained for a fourth day, adding 0.3 percent to 843 by 3:23 p.m.
in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Access Bank Plc (ACCESS NL), a Nigerian lender, climbed 42
kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 8.99 naira, the biggest intraday
increase since Feb. 2. Export-Import Bank of  China  granted
 Access Bank Plc (ACCESS)  a $30 million trade finance facility, Daily
Independent reported today, without saying how it got the
information.  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc (GUARANTY)  , Nigeria’s second-
largest lender by market value, snapped two days of declines,
rising 95 kobo, or 5 percent, to 19.95 naira. Profit for the
year through December climbed 62 percent to 38.3 billion naira,
the company said in a statement on the Nigerian Stock Exchange’s
website today.  Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA NL), Nigeria’s biggest lender by
market value, rallied to the highest in since March 11, adding
73 kobo, or 5 percent, to 15.43 naira. Profit for the year
through December increased 81 percent to 37.4 billion naira
($241.2 million) in the year through December, the bank said in
a statement on the website of the  Nigerian Stock Exchange  today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Vincent Nwanma in Lagos at 
 vnwanma@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
